<subSubSection id="709A01A4FF9AFFF3D5F1FED6FE55FDC7" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="383F522FFF9AFFF3D5F1FED6FE55FDC7" blockId="6.[136,786,279,623]" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">
<emphasis id="0AF48E3DFF9AFFF3D5F1FED6FE3BFE87" box="[174,467,279,303]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">
Notes. – 
<taxonomicName id="FF8029ACFF9AFFF3D455FED6FE3BFE87" authorityName="Scherber. &amp; Duruiss. A. Habit" authorityYear="2017" box="[266,467,279,303]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="pteridoides">Begonia pteridoides</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
was collected by H. Laporte on his last trip to 
<collectingCountry id="409712BFFF9AFFF3D417FEF9FE21FEE7" box="[328,457,311,335]" name="Madagascar" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
, just before he died of a severe form of malaria. It has never been recollected since and unfortunately no herbarium specimens have been sourced. Over the years, living plants have been shared with 
<taxonomicName id="FF8029ACFF9AFFF3D70EFE56FD4CFE07" box="[593,676,408,431]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Begoniaceae" genus="Begonia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Cucurbitales" pageId="6" pageNumber="263" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0AF48E3DFF9AFFF3D70EFE56FD4CFE07" box="[593,676,408,431]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="263">Begonia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
collectors and although it is a very tricky plant to keep alive, it is still present in a few specialized collections and among terrarium growers. The habit is erect in cultivation but a picture taken in situ by H. Laporte, shows a colony of plants growing on granite, with pendent leaves. That habit could reflect a reaction to a momentarily dry period.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
